
{% extends "layout.njk" %}

{% set primaryNavId = 'profile' %}

{% set title = 'Six practical ways schools can reduce the gender pay gap' %}

{% block content %}

  <div class="govuk-grid-row">
    <div class="govuk-grid-column-two-thirds">

        <h1 class="govuk-heading-xl">
            Six practical ways schools can reduce the gender pay gap
        </h1>






        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">
            A guide to fair recruitment best practices
        </h2>

        <p>
            Reducing the gender pay gap (GPG) in education starts with the decisions schools make every day, especially around recruiting, promoting, and retaining staff. While progress is being made across the sector, evidence shows there is more to do, and that even small changes to hiring practice can make a meaningful difference.
        </p>

        <p>
            Teaching Vacancies is designed to support schools to recruit fairly, transparently and inclusively. This short guide sets out straightforward, practical steps schools can take to help reduce their gender pay gap.
        </p>

        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">
            Be clear and transparent about pay
        </h2>

        <p>
            Lack of pay transparency can widen pay gaps over time, particularly where negotiation plays a role. Removing questions about a candidate’s current or previous salary is recognised as essential to preventing the perpetuation of historic pay inequalities. Publishing clear salary information helps all candidates understand what is on offer from the outset.
        </p>

        <p>
            Schools are encouraged to include salary information as part of job listings, helping to set clear expectations and support consistent pay practices across similar roles.
        </p>

        <p>
            Good practice includes:
        </p>

        <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
            <li>
                Including salary ranges or pay scales in job adverts
            </li>
            <li>
                Being clear about progression routes and leadership pathways
            </li>
            <li>
                Avoiding reliance on salary negotiation where possible
            </li> 
        </ul>







        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">
            Use inclusive, gender‑neutral language in adverts
        </h2>

        <p>
            The language used in job adverts can influence who feels encouraged to apply. Inclusive, gender‑neutral wording helps ensure roles feel accessible to a broad range of candidates. We recommend structuring job adverts around clear criteria to keep the focus on what is essential for the role and avoid unnecessary or exclusionary language.
        </p>

        <p>
            Good practice includes:
        </p>

        <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
            <li>
                Avoiding gendercoded language such as “strong leader” or “assertive” (typically associated with masculine coding), and “nurturing” or “empathetic” (typically associated with feminine coding). Instead, use neutral terms like “proven leadership skills” or “interpersonal abilities”
            </li>
            <li>
                Focusing on essential skills and experience
            </li>
            <li>
                Clearly setting out expectations and support available
            </li> 
        </ul>





        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">
            Reduce bias in shortlisting and selection
        </h2>

        <p>
            Unconscious bias can influence recruitment decisions, even where intentions are positive. Blind recruitment - involving structured and anonymised processes - helps ensure candidates are assessed on their skills and experience and is widely accepted as best practice.        
        </p>
        <p>
            Good practice includes:
        </p>

        <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
            <li>
                Using clear, pre‑set shortlisting criteria
            </li>
            <li>
                Removing identifying information where possible
            </li>
            <li>
                Avoiding questions about previous salary
            </li> 
        </ul>








        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">
            Signal flexible working from the start
        </h2>

        <p>
            Flexible working plays a key role in supporting staff with caring responsibilities and improving retention, particularly for women and returners. Schools advertising roles on Teaching Vacancies can clearly indicate flexible, part‑time or job‑share options, making these opportunities visible from the outset.
        </p>
        <p>
            Good practice includes:
        </p>

        <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
            <li>
                Advertising part‑time, job‑share or flexible options upfront
            </li>
            <li>
                Taking a whole‑school approach to flexibility where possible
            </li>
            <li>
                Being open to discussing flexibility at different career stages
            </li> 
        </ul>






        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">
            Support returners and progression into leadership
        </h2>

        <p>
            Women returning after career breaks and those considering leadership roles can face additional barriers. Clear information and supportive signalling can help rebuild confidence and widen access.
        </p>
        <p>
            We recommend schools highlight wellbeing support, workload considerations and development opportunities in their job listings to help candidates understand the support available at different career stages.
        </p>
        <p>
            Good practice includes:
        </p>

        <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
            <li>
                Highlighting wellbeing and workload support
            </li>
            <li>
                Signposting return‑to‑teaching guidance
            </li>
            <li>
                Ensuring development opportunities are accessible at different career stages
            </li> 
        </ul>







        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">
           Monitor, review and take action
        </h2>

        <p>
            Reducing the gender pay gap is an ongoing process. Reviewing recruitment and workforce data helps schools understand the make-up of their workforce, what is working and where further action is needed.
        </p>
        
        <p>
            Good practice includes:
        </p>

        <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
            <li>
                Monitoring recruitment, retention and progression patterns
            </li>
            <li>
                Reviewing leadership diversity over time
            </li>
            <li>
                Publishing gender pay gap information where required and using it to inform action plans
            </li> 
        </ul>

        <p>
            Schools are responsible for their employment decisions and must meet their obligations under the Equality Act 2010 and the Specific Duties and Public Authorities Regulations 2017. From April 2026, employers with 250 or more employees will have the option to produce and publish a voluntary action plan alongside their gender pay gap data. Through these action plans, large employers will be encouraged to publish the steps they are taking to address their gender pay gap and support employees experiencing menopause.
        </p>







        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">
           Supporting fair recruitment with Teaching Vacancies
        </h2>

        <p>
            Teaching Vacancies is the free, government‑run service used by the majority of schools in England. With built‑in tools that promote transparency around pay, flexible working and support, it helps schools conduct fair shortlisting and recruit the best staff while supporting more inclusive employment practices.
        </p>

        <p>
            By taking simple, practical steps, schools can strengthen fair recruitment, support progression and help close the gender pay gap across the education sector.
        </p>
        
        <p>
            Good practice includes:
        </p>

        <p>
            Start listing roles today: <a class="govuk-link" href="#">https://teaching-vacancies.service.gov.uk</a>
        </p>






        <h2 class="govuk-heading-m">
           Quick checklist: practical actions schools can take
        </h2>

        <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
            <li>Include clear salary ranges or pay scales in every job advert</li>
            <li>Use inclusive, gender-neutral language and focus on essential criteria only</li>
            <li>Apply structured and, where possible, anonymised shortlisting</li>
            <li>Avoid asking about previous salary during recruitment</li>
            <li>Clearly advertise flexible, part-time or job-share options</li>
            <li>Highlight support for returners, wellbeing and progression opportunities</li>
            <li>Review recruitment and progression data regularly and take action where needed</li>
        </ul>


    </div>
  </div>

  

{% endblock %}
